    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Circle of Fifths is a cyclical diagram that shows the relationship between keys based on the interval of a perfect fifth. Moving clockwise on the circle adds a sharp, and moving counter-clockwise adds a flat.\n\nTo find the relative minor of a major key, you simply locate the tonic (the root note) of the major key on the circle. Then, you move down three half-steps (or down a minor third) from that tonic. That resulting note is the tonic of the relative minor.\n\nFor example, if you are in Eb Major, the tonic is Eb. Counting down three half-steps from Eb gives you C. Therefore, C minor is the relative minor of Eb Major. This works because both Eb Major and C minor share the same key signature (three flats: Bb, Eb, Ab).",
      "source": "target",
